cmCourseInfo.description: An introduction to concepts and contexts to music education with an emphasis on a critical examination of current practice. Introduction to the basics of various approaches to music teaching and learning.
cmCourseInfo.title: Introduction to Music Education

cmCourseInfo.description: This course introduces students to a variety of ways in which music and musicking are embedded in local communities. Students will critically reflect on current practices and research by leaders in community music engagement. Themes of anti-oppression, belonging, wholeness, and wellbeing will be central to the course.
cmCourseInfo.title: Introduction to Community Music Engagement

cmCourseInfo.description: Introductory study of violin and viola.
cmCourseInfo.title: Instrumental Class: Violin

cmCourseInfo.description: Introductory study of violin and viola.
cmCourseInfo.title: Instrumental Class: Violin

cmCourseInfo.description: Introductory study of the clarinet.
cmCourseInfo.title: Instrumental Class: Clarinet

cmCourseInfo.description: Introductory study of the clarinet.
cmCourseInfo.title: Instrumental Class: Clarinet

cmCourseInfo.description: Introductory study of the trumpet.
cmCourseInfo.title: Instrumental Class: Trumpet

cmCourseInfo.description: Introductory study of the trumpet.
cmCourseInfo.title: Instrumental Class: Trumpet

cmCourseInfo.description: Introductory study of the guitar. Pedagogical considerations for class guitar instruction in popular and classical guitar styles.
cmCourseInfo.title: Instrumental Class: Guitar

cmCourseInfo.description: A practice-based course that develops competency in the playing of chord progressions, simple accompaniments, combinations of parts from open choral scores, combinations of transposing parts from instrumental scores, simple sight harmonization of songs, playing by ear, improvisation, and ensemble playing. A music notation software project will be introduced. This course is limited to those with piano skills at a level equivalent to RCM Level 8 or below.
cmCourseInfo.title: Piano Skills for Professional Musicians/Teachers

cmCourseInfo.description: Introductory study of voice production with attention to breathing technique, tone development and vocal diction. This course focuses on the development of the singing voice for students seeking a basic understanding of how the voice works for singing. Recommended for music education, instrumental, keyboard and composition students interested in singing.
cmCourseInfo.title: Voice Education
cmCourseInfo.exclusionsText: EMU231Y1; Not open to Voice majors

cmCourseInfo.description: Introductory study of vocal methods for teaching young choirs with attention to breathing techniques, tone production, vocal diction and rehearsal pedagogies relevant to working with children and youth choirs. Recommended for all students interested in learning to work vocally with young singers, ages 6-16.
cmCourseInfo.title: Voice Pedagogy for Young Choirs

cmCourseInfo.description: This course introduces students to theoretical inquiry in music education in the context of diversity related to students, teachers, music, and music educational settings. Through course readings, individual research, classroom interactions, presentations, and writing short essays, students critique existing theories, and develop concepts articulating their own theories of music education that take into account relevant social, political, and ethical questions.
cmCourseInfo.title: Theoretical Inquiry in Music Education

cmCourseInfo.description: This course provides an advanced study of the psychological bases of music education. Students will critically reflect on the strengths and weaknesses of prevailing psychological theories in the context of music teaching and learning. Through seminar presentations, research, and the examination of scholarly literature, students will explore the field of music psychology.
cmCourseInfo.title: Psychological Foundations of Music Education

cmCourseInfo.description: Introductory study of the French horn.
cmCourseInfo.title: Instrumental Class: French Horn

cmCourseInfo.description: Introductory study of the trombone.
cmCourseInfo.title: Instrumental Class: Trombone

cmCourseInfo.description: Introductory study of the cello.
cmCourseInfo.title: Instrumental Class: Cello I

cmCourseInfo.description: Practical study of percussion instruments. Care and maintenance of instruments and equipment. Ensemble playing.
cmCourseInfo.title: Instrumental Class: Percussion

cmCourseInfo.description: Introductory study of the oboe.
cmCourseInfo.title: Instrumental Class: Oboe

cmCourseInfo.description: Introductory study of the saxophone.
cmCourseInfo.title: Instrumental Class: Saxophone

cmCourseInfo.description: Introductory study of the double bass. One hour, one term.
cmCourseInfo.title: Instrumental Class: Double Bass

cmCourseInfo.description: The study and practice of choral music with an emphasis on teaching and learning in school and community choral settings. The course will focus on conducting, programming and score study with an emphasis on rehearsal pedagogy.
cmCourseInfo.title: Choral Music Education
cmCourseInfo.prerequisitesText: EMU130Y1, EMU230H1, EMU240H1, EMU245H1 - Education majors only/ In Year 3.

cmCourseInfo.description: The course focuses on developing pianistic, musical and verbal skills in order to succeed in a broad spectrum of collaborative opportunities during a professional career. In-class accompanying presentations and lectures introduce students to professional musician/teacher requirements through collaborative training. Practical experience in improvisation, sight-reading. Assignments appropriate to level of keyboard facility.
cmCourseInfo.title: Accompanying
cmCourseInfo.prerequisitesText: TMU105Y1/TMU107Y1, in Year 2, RCM Grade 9 level Piano or equivalent/P.I.

courses.name: Instrumental Mus: Curriculum, Conducting,Rehearal & Rep. I

cmCourseInfo.description: A study of techniques for the instruction and administration of wind and string instrumental programs. Analysis and performance of beginning and intermediate band and string orchestra repertoire.
cmCourseInfo.title: Instrumental Music I: Curriculum, Conducting, Rehearsal and Repertoire

cmCourseInfo.description: Development of improvisation skills through applied performance and theoretical analysis in a variety of jazz styles.
cmCourseInfo.title: Jazz Improvisation for Music Education

courses.name: Principles & Practice: Mus Ed for Children

cmCourseInfo.description: This course provides an introduction to the philosophical underpinnings and practice-based theories of music education for children. Students will have the opportunity to study the development of musicianship in childhood and explore common theories and educational approaches through seminars, observations, composition and performance experiences, and microteaching opportunities.
cmCourseInfo.title: Principles & Practice of Music Education for Children

cmCourseInfo.description: This course provides a multitude of approaches to music teaching and learning including informal music learning, music technology, community music and improvisatory and creative musical activities in music classrooms. Students will actively create and perform music while crafting a well-rounded curriculum based on the ideas derived from the course. Philosophical underpinnings of such practices will also be examined.
cmCourseInfo.title: Multimodal Approaches to Music Teaching and Learning
cmCourseInfo.prerequisitesText: EMU240H1, EMU245H1 - Education Majors only/In Year 3.

cmCourseInfo.description: This course focuses on the pedagogy of Dalcroze Eurhythmics, a music education approach that examines the intrinsic relationships between physical movement and the learning/performing of music. Students make a kinaesthetic connection to a wide variety of music through invigorating combinations of free movement, choreography, singing, conducting, improvisation and music games.
cmCourseInfo.title: Movement & Music: Dalcroze Eurhythmics

courses.name: Calls to Action through Mus Ed

cmCourseInfo.description: This course takes the Calls to Action from the Truth and Reconciliation Commission as the Foundation for Curriculum and Pedagogy in Music Education. Students will lead seminars on topics related to their research interest and examine current issues facing Indigenous Peoples through the lens of Reconciliation.
cmCourseInfo.title: Calls to Action through Music Education

cmCourseInfo.description: An introduction to modes of research in music education, with particular reference to principles of research design and effective research procedures. Students will prepare critiques of research material and will be guided in designing research projects.
cmCourseInfo.title: Introduction to Research in Music Education

cmCourseInfo.description: The study of choral literature and conducting technique with an emphasis on European classical and Contemporary choral music (including selected choral-orchestral repertoire). The weekly class will meet in a combined literature seminar and conducting practicum with piano and/or small instrumental ensemble.
cmCourseInfo.title: Choral Literature & Conducting I

cmCourseInfo.description: The study of choral literature and conducting technique with an emphasis on European classical and Contemporary choral music (including selected choral-orchestral repertoire). The weekly class will meet in a combined literature and seminar and conducting practicum with piano and/or small instrumental ensemble.
cmCourseInfo.title: Choral Literature & Conducting II

cmCourseInfo.description: This course provides a community-based experience that will enable students to merge theory and practice in music education. Students will volunteer for three hours a week in a community music or school setting of their choosing. Placements must be approved by the instructor during the first week of classes.
cmCourseInfo.title: Internship in Music Education

cmCourseInfo.description: This course provides a community-based experience that will enable students to merge theory and practice in music education. Students will volunteer for three hours a week in a community music or school setting of their choosing. Placements must be approved by the instructor during the first week of classes.
cmCourseInfo.title: Internship in Music Education

cmCourseInfo.description: This course provides a community-based experience that will enable students to merge theory and practice in music education. cmCourseInfo.title: Internship in Music Education

courses.name: Instrumental Mus: Curriculum, Conducting, Rehearsal & Rep II

cmCourseInfo.description: Practical instrumental lab. Selected lecture topics related to teacher effectiveness in an instrumental program. In-field observation and participation.
cmCourseInfo.title: Instrumental Music II: Advanced Curriculum, Conducting, Rehearsal & Repertoire

courses.name: Cultural Perspectives in Music Teaching & Learning

cmCourseInfo.description: A seminar exploring music's social nature, with special attention to the ways culture influences music perception, cognition, and value, and the way musical practices in turn influence culture and social relations. Issues addressed include: music education as intercultural education; music, gender, and power; the educational implications of cultural relativity; music education as an agent of social reproduction and/or transformation; social relations implicit in various musical and instructional practices; and music education's moral significance. Emphasis is placed on practical pedagogical applications of world music.
cmCourseInfo.title: Cultural Perspectives in Music Teaching and Learning
cmCourseInfo.prerequisitesText: EMU240H1, EMU245H1 - Education Majors only/In Year 4.

cmCourseInfo.description: This course invites students to expand their strategies for welcoming children into the diverse practice of musicking. At the core is bell hook’s philosophy of education as a practice of freedom as well as culturally responsive, culturally relevant, and culturally sustaining approaches to music education.
cmCourseInfo.title: Advanced Topics in Music and Childhood

cmCourseInfo.description: An intensive research project under the supervision of a faculty member. The project must be academically demanding and uniquely suitable for the individual student. Students propose a topic that is currently not covered in the curriculum or one that warrants further exploration related to research interests and/or musical goals. Available to students in 4th year on successful completion of several EMU courses; minimum cumulative GPA of 3.3 (B+) and availability of a full-time faculty advisor from the Music Education division. Modes of assessment are determined through discussion between student and supervisor, but will usually include a public presentation of the research project.
cmCourseInfo.title: Independent Study
cmCourseInfo.prerequisitesText: In Year 4. Permission of the Division Required.
